<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1973,1999]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,152,338]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Parafacial hair not different from surrounding hairs and bristles. Apex of gonocoxite not separated (
<bibRefCitation author="Lehr" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" refString="Lehr, P. A. (1989) Robber flies of the subfamily Laphriinae (Diptera, Asilidae) of USSR. Entomologiceskoe Obozreniye, 68 (2), 406 - 421. [English translation: Entomological Review, 68 (6), 121 - 136]." type="journal article" year="1989">
Lehr, 
<number box="[151,214,152,178]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Medium to large bumble bee like flies with long yellow/red hair on thorax and abdomen. The mesal process of the gonopod is complex with dorsal thorns. 
<taxonomicName box="[813,955,192,218]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Laphria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hakiensis">
<emphasis box="[813,829,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[846,955,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">hakiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[972,1128,192,218]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Laphria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitsukurri">
<emphasis box="[972,988,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1006,1128,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">mitsukurri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1189,1272,192,218]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Asilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">
<emphasis box="[1189,1205,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1223,1272,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">rufa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinctly similar in regards to internal male genitalia, and externally different in regards to size and color. Lehr notes (
<number box="[160,224,272,298]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="1989.0">1989</number>
: 
<number box="[236,281,272,298]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="131.0">131</number>
) that, “extreme variations of 
<taxonomicName box="[630,711,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Asilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">
<emphasis box="[630,646,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[662,711,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">rufa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
perfectly fit the description of... 
<taxonomicName box="[1129,1283,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Laphria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitsukurri">
<emphasis box="[1129,1145,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1161,1283,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">mitsukurri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.” (See “Discussion” below.).
</paragraph>
